Project - Image classification using CNNs in Keras¶

- Amarpreet Bassan

Assumptions

  • This notebook is running on Jupyter Colab environment
  • The data file : images.py and Labels.csv is stored in a folder named ConvNetProject in the google drive.
  • This notebook is also present inside the same directory in the google drive.

Configuration for Executing this project:

  • Create a folder named : ConvNetProject in your google drive.
  • Copy the data files : images.npy and Labels.csv and this notebook inside that folder.
  • Execute this notebook from the folder .

In [167]:
#we will convert the image to grayscale
x_gray = np.ndarray((x.shape[0], x.shape[1], x.shape[2]))
try:
  for numimage in range(x.shape[0]):
    x_gray[numimage] = cv2.cvtColor(x[numimage], cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
except Exception as ex:
  print(ex)
  print(numimage)

In [251]:
# we will need to have 12 neurons at the output layer.
# Set the CNN model

batch_size = None

model = models.Sequential()
#Adding 32 input neurons with 9 * 9 filter layer. 
model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (9, 9), padding='same', activation="relu", input_shape=x_train.shape[1:]))
#applying batch normalization
model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
#pooling layer
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
#drop out layer.
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (7, 7), padding='same', activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (5, 5), padding='same', activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (5, 5), padding='same', activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))

model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (5, 5), padding='same', activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))

model.add(layers.GlobalMaxPooling2D())
model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
model.add(layers.Dense(128, activation="relu"))
#model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
model.add(layers.Dense(64, activation="relu"))
#model.add(layers.Dense(32, activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.Dense(12, activation="softmax"))

model.summary()

In [218]:
#Adding Early stopping callback to the fit function is going to stop the training,
#if the val_loss is not going to change even '0.001' for more than 10 continous epochs
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint, EarlyStopping

early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', min_delta=0.001, patience=40)

#Adding Model Checkpoint callback to the fit function is going to save the weights whenever val_loss achieves a new low value. 
#Hence saving the best weights occurred during training

model_checkpoint =  ModelCheckpoint('image_cnn_checkpoint_{epoch:02d}_loss{val_loss:.4f}.h5',
                                                           monitor='val_loss',
                                                           verbose=1,
                                                           save_best_only=True,
                                                           save_weights_only=True,
                                                           mode='auto',
                                                           period=1)

WARNING:tensorflow:`period` argument is deprecated. Please use `save_freq` to specify the frequency in number of batches seen.

Objective 5 - Fit and Evaluate CNN Model¶

Table of Content

In [254]:
history = model.fit(x_train,
                    y_train,
                    batch_size=batch_size,
                    epochs=epochs,
                    validation_data=(x_validation, y_validation),
                    shuffle=True,
                    verbose=1,
                    callbacks=[early_stopping,model_checkpoint])

# plot training history
plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='train')
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='test')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
